{{Sikhism sidebar}}

'''Jathedar''' ({{lang-pa| ਜਥੇਦਾਰ }}), refers to a leader of a [[Jatha]] (a group, a community or a nation).  Among the [[Sikhism|Sikhs]], a Jathedar is an ordained leader of the clergy and leads a [[Takht (Sikhism)|Takht]], a sacred and authoritative seat.

[[Sikh]] clergy consists of five ''Jathedars'', one each from five [[Takht (Sikhism)|takhts]] or sacred seats. The Jathedar of Akal Takht makes all the important decisions after consultations with the Jathedars of the other four Takhts. The highest seat of the Sikh nation is called [[Akal Takht]].

==History==
During the [[18th century]], ''Jathedars'' of [[Takht (Sikhism)|Takhts]] were appointed by the [[Sarbat Khalsa]], a biannual [[Mass meeting|deliberative assembly]] of Sikhs held at [[Amritsar]] in [[Punjab region|Panjab]].

From 1921, ''Jathedars'' of Takhts have been appointed by [[Shiromani Gurdwara Parbandhak Committee]] (SGPC), an elected body of the Sikhs controlled by [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] (SAD), a political party in the state of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] and an ally of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP). 

In November 2015, the [[Sikhs]] appointed four interim ''Jathedars'' through the traditional [[Sarbat Khalsa]] at Chabba village on the outskirts of [[Amritsar]], [[Punjab, India|Panjab]]. Some 100,000 <ref name="The Economist">{{cite news|title=What sounds like a religious schism in Punjab could be a cry for better political leadership|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21679234-what-sounds-religious-schism-punjab-could-be-cry-better-political-leadership-seeking|access-date=15 October 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|date=28 November 2015}}</ref> to 500,000 [[Sikh diaspora|Sikhs]] attended the event from around the world. A few [[Sikh]] organizations did not attend and refused to recognize the resolutions of the event. The congregation of [[Sarbat Khalsa|Sarbat Khalsa 2015]] dismissed the SGPC ''Jathedars'' and appointed interim ''Jathedars'' for [[Akal Takht]], [[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib|Damdama Sahib]] and [[Anandpur Sahib]].

